          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>A patient with long-standing hypertension develops an aortic dissection. Which m</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>A patient with long-standing hypertension develops an aortic dissection. Which mechanism best explains why the vessel wall failed?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Atherosclerotic plaque eroded through the tunica intima</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Atherosclerosis primarily targets the intima of muscular arteries, not the elastic fibres of the aortic media. Aortic dissection involves tearing between wall layers due to weakened elastic tissue, not plaque erosion.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Repeated mechanical stress weakened elastic fibres in the tunica media</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The tunica media of the aorta is packed with elastic fibres that stretch with every heartbeat and recoil as pressure drops. Chronic hypertension subjects these fibres to repeated mechanical stress, gradually weakening them until the wall can no longer hold.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Endothelial dysfunction reduced nitric oxide release</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>While the endothelium releases nitric oxide and other vasoactive substances, the primary mechanism of aortic dissection is mechanical weakening of elastic fibres in the tunica media, not endothelial dysfunction.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Collagen degradation in the tunica adventitia caused wall collapse</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The adventitia contains collagen and fibroblasts and provides external support, but it is not the layer responsible for withstanding arterial blood pressure. Dissection occurs within the media.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "The tunica media contains elastic fibres responsible for the aorta's tensile strength. Chronic hypertension weakens these fibres through repeated mechanical stress, predisposing to dissection."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Exactly right. The aorta's strength comes from elastic fibres in the tunica media. Years of hypertension weaken these fibres through repeated mechanical stress, eventually causing the wall to tear."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
