          },
          "pause": true,
          "displayType": "poster",
          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>A histology slide shows a capillary with a wide, irregular lumen and large gaps </p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>A histology slide shows a capillary with a wide, irregular lumen and large gaps between endothelial cells. In which organ is this capillary type most likely found?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Skeletal muscle</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Skeletal muscle contains continuous capillaries with tight junctions between endothelial cells. These are the most restrictive type and do not have gaps or wide lumens.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Kidney glomerulus</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The kidney glomerulus has fenestrated capillaries with small pores that allow rapid filtration. However, they do not have the large intercellular gaps or irregular lumen described here.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Liver</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Sinusoidal capillaries have wide, irregular lumens and large gaps between endothelial cells, allowing whole blood cells and large proteins to pass through. They are found in the liver, spleen, and bone marrow.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Lung</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Pulmonary alveolar capillaries are continuous capillaries with tight junctions. Their thin walls facilitate gas exchange, but they do not have large intercellular gaps.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "The description matches sinusoidal capillaries, found in the liver, spleen, and bone marrow. Remember the three types: continuous (tight junctions — muscle, skin, lung, CNS), fenestrated (small pores — kidney, intestine, endocrine glands), and sinusoidal (large gaps — liver, spleen, bone marrow)."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Well done. Sinusoidal capillaries in the liver, spleen, and bone marrow have wide lumens and intercellular gaps that allow passage of blood cells and large proteins, reflecting the phagocytic and haematopoietic functions of these organs."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
